 Silke Van Ness, and Suzanne Romaine.\n* {{cite book |first = W. B. |last=Lockwood |title=German Today: The Advanced Learner's Guide |year = 1987 |isbn=978-0-19-815850-9 }}\n* {{cite book |first=Ruth H. |last=Sanders |title=German: Biography of a Language |publisher=Oxford University Press |year = 2010 }} Combines linguistic, anthropological, and historical perspectives in a \"biography\" of German in terms of six \"signal events\" over millennia, including the Battle of Kalkriese, which blocked the spread of Latin-based language north.\n* {{cite book |url = https://books.google.de/books?id=75Z9AAAAIAAJ | ref = harv | last = Hattemer | first = Heinrich | title = Denkmahle des Mittelalters: St. Gallen's altteutsche Sprachsch\u00e6tze | trans-title = Monuments of the Middle Ages: St. Gallen's Old German vocabulary |publisher = Scheitlin und Zollikofer | volume = Vol. 3 | year = 1849 }}\n* {{cite book |url=https://books.google.de/books?id=c7LxaLP5xogC |title=The Origin and Diversification of Language |last=Swadesh |first=Morris |date=1971 |publisher=Transaction Publishers  |isbn=978-0-20-236982-2 |language=en}}\n\n{{refend}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Sister project links |wikt=Category:German language\n|commons=Category:German language\n|b=Category:German language\n|n=no\n|q=German proverbs\n|s=no\n|v=Topic:German\n|voy=German phrasebook\n|species=no\n|d=Q188\n|mw=no\n|m=no\n}}\n{{WikisourceWiki|code=de}}\n{{InterWiki|code=de}}\n* {{Wikisource-inline|list=\n** {{Cite EB1911|wstitle=German Language |short=x |noicon=x}}\n** [[Mark Twain]], [[s:The Awful German Language|The Awful German Language]], 1880\n** [[Carl Schurz]], [[s:The German Mothertongue|The German Mothertongue]], 1897\n** {{Cite AmCyc|wstitle=Germany, Language and Literature of |short=x |noicon=x}}\n}}\n* {{dmoz|Science/Social_Sciences/Linguistics/Languages/Natural/Indo-European/Germanic/German|German (language)}}\n* [http://www.duden.de/ Duden, Germany's top-selling dictionary]\n* [http://dict.leo.org/ende/index_en.html Leo, free online German dictionary]\n* [https://archive.org/details/VerbreitungDerDeutschenSprache Dissemination of the German language in Europe around 1913 (map, 300 dpi)]\n<!-- ======================== {{No more links}} ============================\n    | PLEASE BE CAUTIOUS IN ADDING MORE LINKS TO THIS ARTICLE. Wikipedia  |\n    | is not a collection of links nor should it be used for advertising. |\n    |                                                                     |\n    |           Excessive or inappropriate links WILL BE DELETED.         |\n    | See [[Wikipedia:External links]] & [[Wikipedia:Spam]] for details.  |\n    |                                                                     |\n    | If there are already plentiful links, please propose additions or   |\n    | replacements on this article's discussion page.         |\n=== {{No more links}} =========-->\n\n{{-}}\n{{Languages of Germany}}\n{{Languages of Austria}}\n{{Languages of Switzerland}}\n{{Languages of Namibia}}\n{{Languages of South Africa}}\n{{Germanic languages}}\n{{Germany topics}}\n{{Languages of Europe}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:German language| ]]\n[[Category:Fusional languages]]\n[[Category:High German languages]]\n[[Category:Languages of Austria]]\n[[Category:Languages of Belgium]]\n[[Category:Languages of Denmark]]\n[[Category:Languages of Germany]]\n[[Category:Languages of Liechtenstein]]\n[[Category:Languages of Luxembourg]]\n[[Category:Languages of Namibia]]\n[[Category:Languages of Switzerland]]\n[[Category:Languages of Trentino-Alto Adige/S\u00fcdtirol]]\n[[Category:Stress-timed languages]]\n[[Category:Verb-second languages]]\n", "name_user": "201.157.80.77", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/German_language"}
{"title_page": "Frank Evans (guitarist)", "text_new": "{{Infobox musical artist <!-- See Wikipedia:WikiProject_Musicians -->\n| name                = Frank Evans\n| background       = non_vocal_instrumentalist\n| image               = \n| image_size        = \n| landscape          = \n| caption             = \n| birth_name        = \n| birth_date         = {{birth date|1930|10|1|mf=y}}\n| birth_place        = \n| origin                = \n| death_date        = {{death date and age|2007|2|6|1930|10|1|mf=y}}\n| death_place       = [[Bristol]], [[United Kingdom]]\n| genre                = [[Jazz]]\n| occupation         = [[Guitarist]], [[composer]]\n| instrument         = Guitar\n| years_active      =\n| label                 = Blue Bag Records, 77 Records, Saydisc\n| associated_acts = [[Tubby Hayes]]\n| website             = [https://en-gb.facebook.com/pages/category/Community/Frank-Evans-Jazz-Guitarist-Memory-Page-and-Music-331406862179/ Memory page]\n}}\n\n'''Frank Evans''' (October 1, 1930 \u2013 February 6, 2007) was an [[English people|English]] [[jazz guitarist]].<ref>{{cite web|last=|first=|title=Frank Evans \u2013 Jazz Guitarist 1930-2007|url= https://gypsyjazzuk.wordpress.com/36-2/frank-evans/|work=gypsyjazzuk|publisher=|accessdate=22 September 2019|date=}}</ref>\n\n== Career ==\nEvans took up the guitar at the age of 11 and made his first recording with [[Tubby Hayes]] and [[Tony Coe]] on ''Jazz T\u00eate \u00e0 T\u00eate'', in 1966. After years of extensive touring, Evans focused on his career as a solo jazz guitarist and operated from his home town of [[Bristol]]. In the late 1970s, he set up his own record label called Blue Bag Records and released the solo recordings ''Noctuary'' (BB101), ''Soiree'' (BB102) and ''...For Little Girls'' (BB104).<ref>{{cite book|last=[[Maurice J. Summerfield|Summerfield]]|first=Maurice|date=1978|title=The Jazz Guitar: its evolution and its players|location=|publisher=Ashley Mark|pages=225|isbn=1872639267|publication-date=1978}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|last1=Ingram|first1=Adrian|title=Gibson ES-175: Its History and Players|date=1994|publisher=[[Music Maker Publications|Music Maker Books]]|page=|edition=|url= http://adrianingram.com/ingrambooks.htm}}</ref> The Brazilian guitarist, [[Laurindo Almeida]] recorded the album ''LA3'' (BB103) for the Blue Bag label.<ref>{{cite web|last=|first=|title= Blue Bag Records |url= https://www.discogs.com/label/431382-Blue-Bag|work= |publisher= www.discogs.com |accessdate=22 September 2019|date=}}</ref>\n\nIn February 1978, Evans was featured on the cover of ''Guitar: the magazine for all guitarists''.<ref>{{cite journal |last=Dalton |first=John|title= Guitar: the magazine for all guitarists|publisher=Musical New Services Ltd |publication-place= |date=February 1978|volume=6|issue=7 |pages=13\u201317 |url= https://www.beatchapter.com/guitar-magazine-49f16nproducts97curpage-2-97-c.asp|accessdate= |isbn= |issn= |oclc=|jstor=}}</ref> He was a regular performer on television and radio, including the [[BBC One]] show ''[[Parkinson (TV series)|Parkinson]]'' and an [[ITV (TV network)|ITV]] show called ''Frank Evans and Friends''. As a composer and arranger, he worked on many soundtracks for television drama and documentary programmes.<ref>{{cite book|last=|first=|date=2002|title=International Who's Who in Popular Music 2002|location=|publisher=[[Routledge|Europa Publications]]|pages=877|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=gZIjT8PgJMEC&pg=PA159&lpg=PA159&dq=frank+evans+ballade&source=bl&ots=XBZ0cGUe-_&sig=ACfU3U1pj0_1wQoRg2cERamzFEuU1sesEQ&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwiHpsLvnuTkAhWfQEEAHcpFBakQ6AEwEnoECAYQAQ#v=onepage&q=frank%20evans%20ballade&f=false|isbn=1857431618|publication-date=2002}}</ref> His arrangements for solo guitar have been included in numerous books and guitar publications.<ref>{{cite book|last1=[[Ivor Mairants|Mairants]]|first1=Ivor|title=The Great Jazz Guitarists|date=1994|publisher=Sanctuary Publishing Ltd|page=562|edition=}}</ref>\n\n==Discography==\n* ''Mark Twain'' (1970)\n* ''Stretching Forth'' (1971)\n* ''Noctuary'' (BB101, 1976)\n* ''Soiree'' (BB102, 1977)\n* ''...For Little Girls'' (BB104, n/k)\n\n'''With [[Tubby Hayes]]'''\n* ''Jazz T\u00eate \u00e0 T\u00eate'' (1966)\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Discogs artist|2883783-Frank-Evans-5}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Evans, Frank}}\n[[Category:Musicians from Bristol]]\n[[Category:English jazz guitarists]]\n[[Category:English male guitarists]]\n[[Category:Male jazz musicians]]\n[[Category:1930 births]]\n[[Category:2007 deaths]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox musical artist <!-- See Wikipedia:WikiProject_Musicians -->\n| name                = Frank Evans\n| background       = non_vocal_instrumentalist\n| image               = \n| image_size        = \n| landscape          = \n| caption             = \n| birth_name        = \n| birth_date         = {{birth date|1930|10|1|mf=y}}\n| birth_place        = \n| origin                = \n| death_date        = {{death date and age|2007|2|6|1930|10|1|mf=y}}\n| death_place       = [[Bristol]], [[United Kingdom]]\n| genre                = [[Jazz]]\n| occupation         = [[Guitarist]], [[composer]]\n| instrument         = Guitar\n| years_active      =\n| label                 = Blue Bag Records, 77 Records, Saydisc\n| associated_acts = [[Tubby Hayes]]\n| website             = [https://en-gb.facebook.com/pages/category/Community/Frank-Evans-Jazz-Guitarist-Memory-Page-and-Music-331406862179/ Memory page]\n}}\n\n'''Frank Evans''' (October 1, 1930 \u2013 February 6, 2007) was an [[English people|English]] [[jazz guitarist]].<ref>{{cite web|last=|first=|title=Frank Evans \u2013 Jazz Guitarist 1930-2007|url= https://gypsyjazzuk.wordpress.com/36-2/frank-evans/|work=gypsyjazzuk|publisher=|accessdate=22 September 2019|date=}}</ref>\n\n== Career ==\nEvans took up the guitar at the age of 11 and made his first recording with [[Tubby Hayes]] and [[Tony Coe]] on ''Jazz T\u00eate \u00e0 T\u00eate'', in 1966. After years of extensive touring, Evans focused on his career as a solo jazz guitarist and operated from his home town of [[Bristol]]. In the late 1970s, he set up his own record label called Blue Bag Records and released the solo recordings ''Noctuary'' (BB101), ''Soiree'' (BB102) and ''...For Little Girls'' (BB104).<ref>{{cite book|last=[[Maurice J. Summerfield|Summerfield]]|first=Maurice|date=1978|title=The Jazz Guitar: its evolution and its players|location=|publisher=Ashley Mark|pages=225|isbn=1872639267|publication-date=1978}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|last1=Ingram|first1=Adrian|title=Gibson ES-175: Its History and Players|date=1994|publisher=[[Music Maker Publications|Music Maker Books]]|page=|edition=|url= http://adrianingram.com/ingrambooks.htm}}</ref> The Brazilian guitarist, [[Laurindo Almeida]] recorded the album ''LA3'' (BB103) for the Blue Bag label.<ref>{{cite web|last=|first=|title= Blue Bag Records |url= https://www.discogs.com/label/431382-Blue-Bag|work= |publisher= www.discogs.com |accessdate=22 September 2019|date=}}</ref>\n\nIn February 1978, Evans was featured on the cover of ''Guitar: the magazine for all guitarists''.<ref>{{cite journal |last=Dalton |first=John|title= Guitar: the magazine for all guitarists|publisher=Musical New Services Ltd |publication-place= |date=February 1978|volume=6|issue=7 |pages=13-17 |url= https://www.beatchapter.com/guitar-magazine-49f16nproducts97curpage-2-97-c.asp|accessdate= |isbn= |issn= |oclc=|jstor=}}</ref> He was a regular performer on television and radio, including the [[BBC One]] show ''[[Parkinson (TV series)|Parkinson]]'' and an [[ITV (TV network)|ITV]] show called ''Frank Evans and Friends''. As a composer and arranger, he worked on many soundtracks for television drama and documentary programmes.<ref>{{cite book|last=|first=|date=2002|title=International Who's Who in Popular Music 2002|location=|publisher=[[Routledge|Europa Publications]]|pages=877|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=gZIjT8PgJMEC&pg=PA159&lpg=PA159&dq=frank+evans+ballade&source=bl&ots=XBZ0cGUe-_&sig=ACfU3U1pj0_1wQoRg2cERamzFEuU1sesEQ&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwiHpsLvnuTkAhWfQEEAHcpFBakQ6AEwEnoECAYQAQ#v=onepage&q=frank%20evans%20ballade&f=false|isbn=1857431618|publication-date=2002}}</ref> His arrangements for solo guitar have been included in numerous books and guitar publications.<ref>{{cite book|last1=[[Ivor Mairants|Mairants]]|first1=Ivor|title=The Great Jazz Guitarists|date=1994|publisher=Sanctuary Publishing Ltd|page=562|edition=}}</ref>\n\n==Discography==\n* ''Mark Twain'' (1970)\n* ''Stretching Forth'' (1971)\n* ''Noctuary'' (BB101, 1976)\n* ''Soiree'' (BB102, 1977)\n* ''...For Little Girls'' (BB104, n/k)\n\n'''With [[Tubby Hayes]]'''\n* ''Jazz T\u00eate \u00e0 T\u00eate'' (1966)\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Discogs artist|2883783-Frank-Evans-5}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Evans, Frank}}\n[[Category:Musicians from Bristol]]\n[[Category:English jazz guitarists]]\n[[Category:English male guitarists]]\n[[Category:Male jazz musicians]]\n[[Category:1930 births]]\n[[Category:2007 deaths]]\n", "name_user": "Ser Amantio di Nicolao", "label": "safe", "comment": "add authority control", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Frank_Evans_(guitarist)"}
